]AP[Sabaki:0.51.1];B[qd];W[dp];B[pq];W[dc];B[nd];W[po];B[ql]C[Alex Qi calls this very aggressive, and Black trying to trick White. I don't know why.];W[cf];B[fq]C[Black is luring White to follow-up in the bottom right.];W[cn];B[np];W[qq]C[A little weird. Black got a second move at A, so had White wanted to play this attach, it would've made more sense before Black played A.]LB[np:A];B[qp]C[Also a little weird. Black got a second move at A, so wants to make use of it. This inside hane is counterintuitive - probably still fine. 1-R4-2 would be more intuitive though, as A provides structure to allow for the more aggressive Black 1-2 shape.]LB[np:A][qr:1][rr:2];W[pp];B[rq];W[qr];B[oq]LB[np:A]C[Doesn't A look awkward in this shape?];W[rp];B[qo];W[ro];B[qn];W[rr];B[dq];W[cq];B[cr];W[eq];B[dr];W[ep];B[er];W[fp];B[gq];W[lc];B[jc];W[le];B[mc]C[Standard.](;W[kc]C[This is a mistake. It's too heavy and helps Black become more solid. White can play more lightly at A, then if Black blocks at B, White can play at C, looking to play 1 and 2 in sente. See variation.]LB[mb:A][md:1][nb:B][ne:2][pe:C];B[jd];W[gc];B[jf];W[lg];B[jh];W[li]C[White's group is now heavy.];B[df];W[de];B[cg];W[ef]C[Mistake. Because it helps Black connect A, then White will have to connect at 1. Better to play 1 instead.]LB[ce:1][dg:A];B[dg];W[ce];B[ck];W[eg];B[di];W[qe];B[pe];W[qf];B[rd]C[Black is very efficient in the top right corner.];W[jj];B[hh];W[ei]C[This is a nice move by White. It prepares to attack Black and is sente.];B[ij]LB[dj:A]C[Black should prioritize fixing the shape with A.];W[dj];B[cj]C[Pulling back at A would be more solid. After 1-2, Black would still have issues making enough eyespace.]LB[bj:2][ci:A][ej:1];W[dh];B[ci]LB[ch:A]C[Black must block at A and fight the ko. It's not ideal, but the ko should be OK for Black, and this is too good for White.];W[ch];B[ej];W[ik]LB[fi:A]C[White A would be better. Because it puts more pressure on Black's position, keeps the groups separated, and if Black plays A, it'll help Black connect up.];B[fi];W[eh];B[hj];W[qi];B[fk];W[pn]C[Good timing now that White's developed outside thickness.];B[pm];W[rn];B[qm];W[nn];B[nl];W[om];B[ol]C[The 1-2 exchange helps Black gain outside strength. White would be better of jumping at A, then Black will probably have to take care of the bottom right group with B. After this happens, White can decide if it's worth it to poke at C, or maybe there's a better attack to be had.]LB[kp:B][ln:A][ol:2][om:1][pk:C];W[ln];B[pi];W[ph];B[qj];W[oi];B[pj];W[ri];B[ll]C[Black misses a huge weakness that can be exploited here. Black should cut at A. Because if White pulls back at B, Black can capture a stone at C anytime, which provides immediate eyespace relief. And of course, if White chooses to attack Black A, White could easily lose 2 stones.

Furthermore, if Black chooses not to play A, Black 1 is more urgent now.]LB[kp:1][ni:C][oh:A][pg:B]TR[qi][ri];W[oj]LB[oh:A]C[A mistake. White should mind his own weaknesses instead. Black's cut at A is severe. See variation.](;B[km];W[oc];B[pc]C[Big mistake. Because now White can connect at A, and use B and C to develop eyespace. Black should extend at A, punishing White for invading so deeply.]LB[jb:C][mb:A][nb:B](;W[od]LB[mb:A]C[This is too fancy. Better to connect at A. While this move isn't bad, it creates a burden of having to read precisely.];B[oe];W[mb];B[nc];W[ob];B[nb];W[na];B[me]C[This result is favorable for White.](;W[ma]C[Blunder. Because Black is so strong nearby, the wedge at A is devastating. White 1 defends against Black A.]TR[jc][jd][jf][jh][mc][me][nd][oe][pe][qh]LB[kb:1][lf:A](;B[ke]LB[lf:A]C[Black misses the vital point at A.];W[ld];B[lf];W[mf];B[kf];W[nf];B[ne];W[pd];B[pb];W[oa];B[pa];W[lb]C[This result is favorable for White. Black's corner isn't alive yet, and White can kill at A.]LB[rb:A];B[kp];W[ko];B[jo];W[lp];B[kq](;W[kn]C[Mistake. Because it ony helps Black solidify the outside. White A is better. See variation.]LB[lq:A];B[jn](;W[mp]C[This is a difficult position for White. White may have an easier time sacrificing 5 stones, and drop down at A.

But dropping down at A is scary. It's a complicated read. See variations.]LB[lq:A]TR[nn][om][pn][po][pp];B[no]C[This bump creates problems for White.];W[mo];B[on]LB[mr:A]C[Black A is the vital point. These exchanges are fine, but Black A is most powerful.];W[oo];B[op](;W[on]LB[mr:A]C[White should sacrifice 4 stones and block at A. Because otherwise, Black will play there and White's whole group will die. See variation.];B[nm];W[mn];B[mq]LB[mr:A]C[Big mistake. The vital point is Black A. That would thoroughly kill White's group and make up for the previous mistake in the top right corner.];W[lq];B[mr]C[Another mistake. Black can manage the situation with A, preparing to start the ko at B. It's the best option after missing the vital point previously.]LB[lr:A][nr:B];W[lr];B[kr];W[nr];B[ns];W[or];B[pr];W[ps];B[nq];W[ms]C[hand-talk: Thank you for the game
