])(;W[mr];B[on];W[lq];B[kr];W[ns]C[White can threaten to make an eye and connect up like this.]))(;W[lq];B[mo]C[Here, White must understand the marked stones are dead weight. If White saves them, it becomes an all-or-nothing exchange. If White can abandon them in order to make life, that would be the more pragmatic option.]TR[nn][om][pn][po][pp];W[mn];B[lo];W[kr];B[jr];W[mr];B[no]C[Black has this simple move which makes things difficult for White.];W[pr];B[on]C[This capturing race is in Black's favor.];W[oo];B[op];W[on];B[or];W[os];B[lm];W[nr];B[mm]C[Black wins this capturing race.]))(;W[lq];B[mo]TR[nn][om][pn][po][pp]C[White must understand these 5 stones are dead weight. Trying to save them will result in an all-or-nothing exchange. If they can be sacrificed to make life, that's the pragmatic option.];W[lo];B[mn];W[jn];B[io];W[kr];B[jr];W[mr]TR[nn][om][pn][po][pp]C[It's true that losing those 5 stones is a local loss. But given winning the fight at the top right, this is still a global victory.]))(;B[lf];W[kf];B[ld];W[mf];B[kd]C[Oof.]))(;W[kb];B[lf];W[kf];B[ld];W[mf];B[kd];W[jb];B[ib];W[hb]C[White 1 allows White to connect to White 2 like this. The reading is tricky though. It gets messy if Black A - White B - Black C.]LB[gc:2][ia:A][ic:B][kb:1][la:C]))(;W[mb];B[nc];W[nb];B[ob];W[jb];B[ib];W[kb];B[hc];W[la]C[White lives like this.]))(;B[oh];W[pg];B[nh];W[mj];B[nf]C[This will be severe later in the game.];W[rj]C[White can live.];B[rk];W[rg];B[km]C[And now the tables have turned. Black has separated White, forced White to live in gote, and continues attacking the other half. A headache for White.]))(;W[mb];B[nb];W[pe](;B[pd]C[If Black responds passively...];W[md];B[nc];W[ne]C[White gets a lovely result.])(;B[mf]C[Black responds assertively.];W[oc];B[nc];W[qe];B[pc];W[qi]C[Black gets a solid position on the top, White gets a nice side extension. This is still better than the 1-2 exchange earlier.]LB[jd:2][kc:1])))